Diagnosis.
The new species is assigned to the genus 

Rhacophorus

by the presence of intercalary cartilage between the terminal and penultimate phalanges of digits, Y-shaped distal end of terminal phalanx, tips of digits expanded into large disks bearing circummarginal grooves, webbed fingers, a supracloacal dermal ridge, vomerine teeth, and horizontal pupil (

Brown & Alcala 
1994

; 

Duellman & Trueb 
1986

; 

Liem 
1970

). 

Rhacophorus vampyrus

is distinguished from all other 

Rhacophorus

in mainland Southeast Asia by a combination of (
1
) pale tan to brick red dorsum, (
2
) white throat, chest and belly, (
3
) mostly black flanks and anterior and posterior surface of thighs, (
4
) grey to black webbing between fingers and toes, (
5
) reduced finger webbing, and (
6
) pointed projection at tibiotarsal articulation.
